  1. Installing CRONO


  After download the package crono-XXX.tar.gz, you must unpack in a
  temporary directory.

   # cd /<tmp_directory>
        # gunzip crono-XXX.tar.gz
        # tar -xvf crono-XXX.tar

  The list below shows the files and directories that will be created.

   COPYING
   Changelog
   README
   bin/               -> User programs (after compilation)
   docs/
   docs/Adm-Manual    -> Administrator Manual
   docs/User-Manual   -> User Manual
   docs/UI-API-Manual -> API for the User Interface Commands (for developers) 
   etc/
   etc/amconf         -> Example of amconf file (Section 2.9 and User-Manual)
   etc/homogeneous    -> Example of a homogeneous cluster configuration
   etc/heterogeneous  -> Example of a heterogeneous cluster configuration
   sbin/              -> Daemons (after compilation)
   src/               -> Source code

  Before compiling CRONO, some default configurations can be modified in the
  src/Makefile.defs. Modify them if necessary.
   
  Next, change to the 'src' directory, type 'make' to build and 'make install'
  to install the binaries and configuration files.

   # cd src
   # make
   # make install

  After that, you'll have the following programs:

   In the 'bin' directory:
   -> User Interface programs

   In the 'sbin' directory:
   -> Access Manager daemon: cramd
   -> Request Manager daemon: crrmd
   -> Node Manager daemon: crnmd

   In the 'etc' directory:
   -> Example of a cluster configuration: 'tropical' directory

   For information about the User Interface programs, please consult the User
   Manual.



  2. Configuration


  This session describes the CRONO's configuration files, as well as the
  structure of the directory where they are found. Assuming that you have
  installed CRONO in the /usr/local/ directory, the configuration files
  will be in /usr/local/etc/ directory, and we'll call it DIRCONF.

  The DIRCONF structure is:

  <dirconf>/
   amconf - this file contains the hostname and port for Access Manager
   <cluster1>/ - configuration for cluster1
   <cluster2>/ - configuration for cluster2
   ...
   ...

  For each directory we have:

  <clusterN>/
   crono.conf         - Hostnames and ports used by the daemons, queue and log
                        files, and other options.
   groups             - Group of users.
   accessrights.defs  - Access Rights definitions.
   nodes              - Nodes of the cluster.
   commands           - Commands that the users can execute on the nodes.
   mpreps          - Master Pre-processing Script.
   mpostps         - Master Post-processing Script.
   hosts.equiv        - Original /etc/hosts.equiv file.
   login.access       - Original /etc/security/access.conf (or /etc/login.access)
                        file.


  2.1 crono.conf

  This is the main cluster configuration file. Here you have to specify the
  hostname where each system manager is executed, the listened port, the path of
  the log, pids and the requests queue, the number of users that can share a
  node at same time, PAM support and timeout of connections between Request
  Manager and Node Manager.

  If you are interested to run CRONO on a single machine (not in a cluster),
  it's necessary to turn on the single option (single=on) in the crono.conf
  file. With this option the Request Manager ignores the function calls that
  make communication to the Node Manager. 

  A typical crono.conf file:

  #################################################################
  # CLUSTER: cluster1
  #################################################################

  # Server ports
  amport=7001
  rmport=7022
  nmport=7004

  # Server hosts
  amhost=servername
  rmhost=servername

  # Number of users that can share a node at the same time(time-sharing)
  share=2

  # Single Option (off-> there is a cluster available)
  #               (on-> there is not a cluster available)
  single=off

  # PAM support (on or off)
  pam=on

  #Connection Timeout in seconds
  conntimeout=1

  # Timeout of Master pre-processing script
  tmpreps=2

  # Timeout of Master post-processing script 
  tmpostps=2
  
  # Log File
  logfile=/usr/local/var/log/crono_cluster1.log

  # Queue File
  queuefile=/usr/local/var/queues/crono_cluster1.queue

  # Process IDs Directory
  piddir=/usr/local/var/pid/

  #################################################################

  For details of how PAM support option is used on CRONO, see the Section 2.7
  of this manual.

  If the nodes are in the same network of the machine that the Request Manager
  is running, use a low value, like 1. Otherwise, use a higher value.   

  2.2 groups

  In this file it's possible to specify the group name and their members. This
  file could be modified while the daemons are running.
  Example of the groups file:

  #################################################################
  # group <group name>
  #    <user>
  #    <user>
  #     ...
  # endgroup
  #   ...
  #################################################################
  group master
     student1
     student2
     student3
  endgroup
  group group2
     linux
     unix
     freebsd
  endgroup
  #################################################################


  2.3 accessrights.defs

  This file defines the user and user groups access rights. In each access
  right profile it is possible to define the time, number of nodes and number
  of future allocations (reserves) both in normal and special time.

  This file could be modified while the daemons are running.

  The syntax is illustrated as follows:

  ######################################################################
  # Access Rights configuration file
  #
  # special
  #    <week day> <initial time>-<final time>
  #    <week day> <initial time>-<final time>
  #     ...
  # endspecial
  #
  #users: <user|group> [ <user|group> <user|group> .... ]
  #[ defaults: <options> ]
  #nodetype <nodetype>: <options>
  #[ nodetype <nodetype>: <options> ]
  #...
  #
  ###################################################################### 
  # options: 
  #    time=<time>             : time for normal period
  #    stime=<stime>           : time for special period
  #    nnodes=<nnodes>         : number of nodes for normal period
  #    snnodes=<snnodes>       : number of nodes for special period
  #    nreserves=<nreserves>   : number of reserves for normal period
  #    snreserves=<snreserves> : number of reserves for special period
  #
  ######################################################################

  Some important issues about this file:

  1) When some option is not specified, its value is zero;
  2) When some option of the normal period is specified and its correspondent
     options (in special period) is not specified, the special option receives
     the value of the normal option.
     Ex.:  time=30 nnodes=8
           
           The value of stime will be 30 and snnodes will be 8.
  
  3) It is possible to specify a user called "default". When a user
     (or its group) is not specified anywhere and the "default" is,
     such a user receives the specification of the "default" profile.

  4) The "defaults" option of a user is useful when the managed cluster
     is composed of heterogeneous clusters:
     Ex.:
          users: masters phds student5
          defaults: time=30 stime=60 nreserves=0 snreserves=2
          nodetype p3: nnodes=16
          nodetype p4: nnodes=4 snnodes=8

    In this example, for both nodetypes, the time and the number of reserves
    are the same.

   Two examples of accessrights.defs files can be found in DIRCONF directory.
   One for homogeneous cluster and another one for heterogeneous cluster.

  2.4 nodes

  The hostname of each node must be included in this file. The Request Manager
  reads this file looking for the nodes under its responsibility.
  This file must also have the specification of the cluster node types.
  The arch variable must be 'ia32' or 'ia64' because of the 'crcomp' and 'crrun'
  commands. If you won't use the 'crcomp' and 'crrun' commands, you
  can use any value for arch variable.
  The syntax of the nodes file is:
  
  TYPES
   
  type=<nodetype>,arch=<architecture>,nprocs=<numb. of procs>,desc=<description>
  type=<nodetype>,arch=<architecture>,nprocs=<numb. of procs>,desc=<description>
  ...

  NODES

  <hostname>:<nodetype>
  <hostname>:<nodetype>
  ...

  Below there is an example of the nodes file: 
  ##############################################################################
  TYPES

  type=p3-550,arch=ia32,nprocs=1,desc="mem=256MB,cpu=2*1Ghz, no video"
  type=p3-550v,typebase=p3-550,desc="p3-550 with video and monitor"
  type=p3-1000,arch=ia32,nprocs=4,desc="mem=256MB,cpu=1Ghz, no video"
  type=p4-2000,arch=ia32,nprocs=4,desc="mem=512MB,cpu=2Ghz, no video"
  #Itanium nodes
  type=ipf,arch=ia64,nprocs=8,desc="mem=1GB,cpu=900Mhz, no video"

  NODES

  cluster1_1:p3-550,p3-550v
  cluster1_2:p3-550
  cluster1_3:p3-550
  cluster1_4:p3-550
  cluster1_5:p3-1000
  cluster1_6:p3-1000
  cluster1_7:p3-1000
  cluster1_8:p3-2000
  cluster1_9:p3-2000
  cluster1_10:ipf
  cluster1_11:ipf
                                   
  ##############################################################################
  If you want to use the crrun command, in nodes which have more than
  one type, put the base type before the other types:

     cluster1_1:p3-550,p3-550v   -> RIGHT
     cluster1_1:p3-550v,p3-550   -> WRONG

  This is due to the creation of the machine files.


  2.5 commands

  This file defines the user operations that are allowed to execute on the
  nodes, through the crnmc tool. For example: the "killp" operation allows
  to finalize the processes of the user in a list of nodes specified by him/her.

  #################################################################
  # <operation>: <command>
  killp: skill -KILL -u $CR_USERNAME
  #################################################################
  
  The CR_USERNAME,CR_USERID and CR_CLUSTER are the available variables that
  can be used in this file.


  2.6 mpreps and mpostps


  The Master Pre-processing Script (MPREPS) and Master Post-processing Script
  (MPOSTPS) are executed, respectively, at the start or finish user time. 
  They're shell scripts that are called by the Request Manager and have some
  variables available:
     - CR_CLUSTER   = cluster name
     - CR_USERID    = user id
     - CR_USERNAME  = user name
     - CR_NODES     = list of user nodes (e.g. : "tropical01 tropical02")
     - CR_NODESINFO  = list of user nodes with additional information
          Format: (for each node) 
             <hostname>:<nodetype>:<architecture>:
             <number of processes>:"<description>"<space>
     - CR_RID      = request id
  Example of usage:

  #!/bin/sh
  # Master Pre-Processing Script
  #
  # build machine files for MPI Ethernet (see tools Section 4.2)

  $CRONOBIN/crmkmachfile -u $CR_USERID -c amazonia\
  -env mpiether -n `eval $CRONOBIN/crnodesinfofilter $CR_NODESINFO`

  # build machine files for MPI GM (see tools Section 4.2)

  $CRONOBIN/crmkmachfile -u $CR_USERID -c amazonia\
  -env mpigm -n `eval $CRONOBIN/crnodesinfofilter $CR_NODESINFO`

  #################################################################

  #################################################################
  #!/bin/sh
  # Master Post-Processing Script
  #
  crwritelogend $CR_USERNAME  # log for finishing resources use
  # (crwritelogend doesn't exist, it is just an example
  #################################################################

  The mpreps and mpostps can be either scripts or programs.

  2.7 login.access (or access.conf), hosts.equiv and PAM

  In order to make possible the nodes to be accessed by only the allowed users,
  CRONO modifies one file (if PAM is used) or two files (if PAM is NOT used) 
  through the Node Manager.
  PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules) are at the core of user
  authentication in most linux distributions, like Debian, Red Hat and Mandrake.
  Slackware is an example of distribution which doesn't use PAM. 

  2.8.1 Linux distributions with PAM 

  If PAM is used, CRONO will modify only the login.access file in each start
  or finish time of a user allocation.
  Probably this file is called by those distributions like "access.conf"
  and its path is /etc/security/access.conf .
  For example, if you want to release the access for "root" and "crono"
  users (that is, these users don't need to use cralloc command to have the
  access to the nodes), you have to set up the login.access in the cluster
  configuration directory (e.g. DIRCONF/cluster1/login.access):
  #################################################################
  # login.access
  # Free access for root and crono users
  #
  -:ALL EXCEPT root crono :ALL
  #################################################################

  It's necessary to configure the PAM to read the access.conf every time when
  the user login or execute a rsh on a node.
  In order to do this, you have to modify three PAM files on each node:
     /etc/pam.d/rsh
     /etc/pam.d/rlogin
     /etc/pam.d/login

  Just add the following lines on these in "rlogin" and "rsh":
    auth    sufficient      pam_rootok.so
    account    required     pam_access.so

  Uncomment the following line in "login":
    account  required       pam_access.so

  And remove the following line (in rsh, rlogin and login files):
    auth            sufficient      pam_rhosts_auth.so

  These files and paths may vary on which linux distribution you have.

  2.8.2 Linux distributions without PAM 

  If PAM is NOT used, CRONO will modify the login.access and hosts.equiv files
  in each start or finish time of a user allocation.
  For example, if you want to release the access for "root" and "crono"
  users (that is, these users don't need to use cralloc command to have the
  access to the nodes), we have to set up the login.access in the cluster
  configuration directory (e.g. DIRCONF/cluster1/login.access):
  #################################################################
  # login.access
  # Free access for root and crono users
  #
  -:ALL EXCEPT root crono :ALL
  #################################################################

  The login.access grants the access to the nodes only to the authorized users.
  The hosts.equiv file filters nodes access by using the rsh command (remote
  shell). Your rsh server must be started with an option to ignore the .rhosts
  file (Slackware distribution starts the server (shell and login) in 
  /etc/inetd.conf and uses the -l -h flag to ignore the .rhosts).
  Example of DIRCONF/cluster1/hosts.equiv:

  #################################################################
  # hosts.equiv
  localhost
  + stelmar
  #################################################################


  2.9 amconf

  This file is very simple and contains the hostname and port of the Access
  Manager. This file is used by the User Interface tools to identify where is
  the AM.
  An example of the amconf file is:

  #################################################################
  # <hostname> <port>
  servername 7001
  #################################################################



  3 CRONO Daemons 


  3.1 Access Manager (cramd) (AM)

  This daemon is used to receive requests from users, check the users access
  rights and then forward the requests to the Requests Manager. A CRONO Access
  Manager daemon can control more than one Requests Manager. Don't forget to set
  the right ports and hostnames in the crono.conf file.

  Usage: cramd [-v] [-d <dirconf> ] <cluster1> ...
         cramd --help
          -v              : Verbose mode
          -d <dirconf>    : Configuration directory
          --help          : Display this help and exit

  Examples:
  If you have one cluster use:
      cramd cluster1
  If you have more than one cluster use:
      cramd cluster1 cluster2 cluster2

  Configuration files needed to execute AM:
     - crono.conf
     - groups
     - accessrights.defs
     - accessrights.users
     - nodes
     - commands (if crnmc command is used)

  3.2 Request Manager (crrmd) (RM)

  This daemon receives the requests from the Access Manager and it is
  responsible for scheduling the allocation requests. The crrmd daemon can
  control only one cluster. Each time that the requests queue is changed, the
  Request Manager store the queue on a file (defined in crono.conf file). If
  the crrmd daemon is killed, your machine has crashed or another thing as
  happened, you can retrieve the queue.

  Usage: crrmd [-v] [-d <dirconf>]  [-c]  <cluster>
       crrmd -k <cluster>
       crrmd --help

        -v              : Verbose mode
        -c              : Clear the queue file if it exists 
        -d <dirconf>    : Configuration directory
        -k <cluster>    : Kill crrmd
        --help          : Display this help and exit

  Example:
      crrmd cluster1

  The Request Manager tries to retrieve the queue if the -c option is not
  used.

  Configuration files needed to execute RM:
     - crono.conf
     - nodes
     - mpreps and mpostps (optional)

  3.3 Node Manager (crnmd) (NM)

  This daemon is used to change the contents of the /etc/hosts.equiv and the
  /etc/login.access files to protect the nodes from users that are not
  allowed to use them. It is also responsible for receiving requests from the
  Request Manager for the execution of 'special commands'. Each cluster node
  must have a crnmd daemon.

  Usage: crnmd [-v] [-d <dirconf> ] <cluster>
         crnmd -k <cluster>
         crnmd --help
          -v              : Verbose mode
          -d <dirconf>    : Configuration directory
          -k <cluster>    : Kill crnmd
          --help          : Display this help and exit

  Example:
      crnmd tropical
 
  Configuration files needed to execute NM:
     - crono.conf
     - commands (if crnmc command is used)
     - login.access (or access.conf)
     - hosts.equiv (if PAM is not used)

  3.4 How to start the daemons

  There is no order to start the CRONO daemons. A good way to start
  them is the following:

  Log on host machine (machine used to run user programs) and type:
      $ cramd cluster1
      $ crrmd cluster1

  After this, you will have to start the crnmd daemons in all cluster nodes.
  You can use a script like this:

  #!/bin/sh
  COMMAND="/usr/local/sbin/crnmd cluster1"
  MACH=cluster1
  for machine in `seq 1 8`
  do
      echo "rsh $MACH$machine $COMMAND"
      rsh $MACH$machine $COMMAND
  done

  It's a good idea to start the daemons using the init scripts of Linux (rc.*),
  on the front-end and on the each node.


  3.5. How to stop the daemons

  As you do not have an order to start de deamons, there is no order to
  finalize them.
  Below are the steps to do it:

  To finalize the crnmd daemon of the cluster1:
     $ crnmd -k cluster1

  To finalize the crrmd daemon of the cluster1:
     $ crrmd -k cluster1

  To finalize the cramd daemon there is a little difference to the above
  commands. This is because a cramd can manage more than one cluster. If your
  cramd daemon was started like:
     $ cramd cluster1

  you can finalize it by this way:
     $ cramd -k cluster1

  But if you started this daemon like this (to manage more than one cluster),
  for example:
     $ cramd cluster1 cluster2 cluster3

  you must specify the first cluster used to start the daemon. So, use this
  command to finish it:
     $ cramd -k cluster1


  4. Administrative Tools

  4.1. crstat

  The crstat is a very simple administrative tool that allows the Administrator
  to have some clusters usage information. It uses the log file generated by
  CRONO to show the information.

   Usage: crstat -f <log> -n <nnodes> [ -d <ndays> ]
       crqview --help           
                                
        -f <log>                : Log file generated by Crono
        -n <nnodes>             : Number of nodes the cluster has
        -d <ndays>              : Number of days of the month
        --help                  : Display this help and exit

    Examples:

      # crstat -f /usr/local/var/log/crono_cluster1.log -n 16
      # crstat -f /usr/local/var/log/crono_cluster1.log -n 16 -d 15

      And the result is something like this:

      001> User: user14         Time: 413     minutes
      002> User: bach           Time: 327     minutes
      003> User: vivaldi        Time: 231     minutes

       AVERAGE UTILIZATION: 16.616 %

    When crstat opens the log file, it figures out the number of days based on
    the month found in the first line of the file. The "-d" file can be useful
    when you need to verify statistics during the current month, or you do not
    want to consider some days of the month.


  4.2. crnodesinfofilter
   
  This tool is a filter which receives as input the $CR_NODESINFO variable
  and generates the following output:
 
  <node type>:<arch>:<nprocs> <node1> <node2> ... <node type>:<arch>:<nprocs>
  <node3> <node4> ... <node type>:<arch>:<nprocs> <node1> <node2>....

  This output is used by the crmkmachfile.
  

  4.3. crmkmachfile

  Using this tool, you will be able to create the machines files used by MPI
  to execute the applications.

  Usage: crmkmachfile -c <cluster> -env <environment>
                   [-u <uid> ] -n <type>:<arch>:<nprocs> <node1> <node2> ...
                                  <type>:<arch>:<nprocs> <node3> <node4> ...
       crmkmachfile -l
       crmkmachfile --help

        -c <cluster>            : Cluster name
        -env <environment>      : Environment name
        -u <uid>                : User identification (option only for root)
        -n                      : List of nodes
        -l                      : Show the supported environments
        --help                  : Display this help and exit

  Ex.: crmkmachfile -c tropical -env mpiether -u 1001 -n ia32:e800=4 \
       tropical01 tropical02 ia64:ipf=10 tropical05 tropical06

  The files are in $HOME/.crono/machfile.<cluster>.<arch>.<environment> .
  Ex.: /home/stelmar/.crono/machfile.tropical.ia64.mpiether

  In general, in order to create the machine files, you can use the following
  line in the mpreps.sh file:
   

   /usr/local/crono/bin/crmkmachfile -u $CR_USERID -c tropical\
   -env mpiether -n `eval /usr/local/crono/bin/crnodesinfofilter $CR_NODESINFO`


  5. Scripts crrun and crcomp

  There are two wrapper scripts to help users to compile and run programs:
  crcomp and crrun. The first one is useful in environments which have more
  than on Mpi.
  So the Administrator defines, for example, the Mpi directories and you can
  choose one of the Mpi versions available. The second one is used to run
  programs. In this second script you have to specify the environment, the
  cluster, and optionality the architecture which will be used to run the
  programs.
  Below are just examples of the usage of these scripts.

  To compile: crcomp (CRONO Compiler)

  The user can specify if he/she wants an executable for a specific
  architecture or not. For this procedure the user can provide the flag
   "-arch <arch_name>". Possible values for this flag are defined by the
  administrator (in general "ia32" and "ia64"). When the user doesn't specify
  this flag, it will be generated two executables for all the available
  architectures. In this case, one will add an extension in the executable
  with the architecture names (like myprog.ia32 and myprog.ia64).

   Usage: crcomp -env <mpicomp> [ -arch <arch> ] [options]

   If -arch is not specified, one will compile for both architectures

   Ex1.: crcomp -env mpiethercc hello.c -o hello
   Ex2.: crcomp -env mpiethercc -arch ia64 hello.c -o hello


  To run: crrun (CRONO Runner)

  Usage: crrun -c <cluster> -env <mpirun> [-arch <arch> ] [options]

   If -arch is not specified, one will run on the available architectures.

   Ex1.: crrun -c amazonia -env mpiether -arch ia32 -np 8 hello
   Ex2.: crrun -c amazonia -env mpigm -np 16 multiply 20 30

  If the user has nodes of more than one architecture, crrun will look for the
  extensions of all architecture names (like ".ia32" and ".ia64").
  If the user doesn't want to use extensions, he/she can use the %a symbol,
  for example /home/stelmar/%a/myprog.

  When the user time starts, CRONO can create the machine files for all
  execution environments. Therefore the "-machinefile" parameter will not
  be used by the user.
  To simplify the command line the user will pass just one "-np" and the
  crrun command will create more than one "-np" (if necessary).

  For example, suppose two machine files:
  - IA64 machines:
       amazonia01
       amazonia02

 - IA32 machines:
       amazonia03
       amazonia04
       amazonia05

  When the user gives "-np 3" crrun will create "-np 2" and "-np 1".
  When the user gives "-np 5" crrun will create "-np 2" and "-np 3".
  When the user gives "-np 7" crrun will create "-np 4" and "-np 3".
  When the user gives "-np 9" crrun will create "-np 4" and "-np 5".
  And so on.

  Note  that the "best" machines will be used before the others.
  In our case, the IA64 will be used before the iA32.

  The machine files are stored in:
     $HOME/.crono/machfile.<cluster>.<arch>.<environment>


  The crrun and crcomp scripts available with the CRONO system are just examples
  of scripts. They work very well on our environment (CPAD), but probably
  you have to adapt them.

